# EKS Best Practices

## Cluster Configuration
- Use private API server endpoint; restrict public access to VPN/bastion CIDRs if enabled
- Enable control plane logging: API server, audit, authenticator
- Use EKS Access Entries (not aws-auth ConfigMap) for IAM-to-RBAC mapping
- Pin EKS add-on versions; upgrade alongside cluster
- **Cluster boundary:** use separate clusters for production vs non-production (isolation, blast radius, compliance); consider multi-cluster when teams need independent upgrade cadences or regulatory separation requires it

## Node Management
- **Multi-AZ:** distribute nodes across at least 2 AZs (3 preferred) to match control plane resilience; single-AZ clusters are acceptable only for non-production/cost-constrained environments
- Use Karpenter for **node-level** autoscaling with consolidation enabled
- Prefer Graviton (ARM) instances for cost-performance (20-40% savings)
- Use Spot instances for fault-tolerant workloads; **mix Spot + On-Demand** to avoid compounded failures (Spot interruption + AZ outage)
- **Failure domain awareness:** avoid placing all replicas on a single node group or instance type; diversify instance families so that a capacity event in one pool does not take all replicas
- Set appropriate instance types per workload: compute-optimized, memory-optimized
- Enable prefix delegation for high pod density

## Workload Standards
- Set resource `requests` and `limits` on all containers
- Use `topologySpreadConstraints` to distribute pods across AZs (workloads must match multi-AZ node topology)
- Configure PodDisruptionBudgets on all production deployments
- **Probes and graceful shutdown:** configure `readinessProbe` (traffic gating), `livenessProbe` (restart on hang), and adequate `terminationGracePeriodSeconds` (long enough for in-flight requests to drain); without these, scaling events and rollouts cause cascading failures
- Run containers as non-root with read-only root filesystem
- Use dedicated ServiceAccounts with IRSA per workload
- **Pod-level scaling:** use HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) for request-driven workloads; consider VPA for right-sizing requests on stable workloads. Scaling is two-dimensional: HPA scales pods, Karpenter scales nodes to fit them

## Networking
- Use AWS Load Balancer Controller for ALB/NLB management
- Set target type to `ip` for direct pod routing
- Enable Network Policies (VPC CNI built-in) with default deny
- Use VPC endpoints for ECR, S3, STS, and other AWS services

## Upgrades
- Upgrade one minor version at a time
- Sequence: control plane → managed add-ons → data plane → self-managed add-ons
- Check API deprecations before upgrading
- Test upgrades in non-production first
- Back up cluster state with Velero before upgrade

## Observability
- Deploy Datadog agent (DaemonSet + Cluster Agent) for metrics, logs, traces
- Enable Orchestrator Explorer for Kubernetes resource visibility
- Use unified service tagging (`env`, `service`, `version`) on all workloads
- Alert on node NotReady, pod CrashLoopBackOff, and HPA max replicas
